		<h3>Frequently Asked Questions about COVID-19 and Children<br>
</h3>
		
		
		
		
		
		
		
			<span class="text rteSpan"><p style="mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto;
background:white">  </p>
<p><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>The CDC has developed a list of <b><i>Frequently Asked Questions</i></b> regarding COVID-19 and children. The questions, answers, and resources are included below. Answers to other questions can be found at: <a target="_blank" href="https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/faq.html#COVID-19-and-Children">https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/faq.html#COVID-19-and-Children</a></span></p>
<p><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'><a target="_blank" href="https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/faq.html#COVID-19-and-Children"></a><br></span></p>
<p style="mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto;
background:white">  <span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'><b>CDC: COVID-19 and Children – Frequently Asked Questions</b></span></p>  <p style="mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto;
background:white"><b><u><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:#007C91'>What is the risk of my child becoming sick with COVID-19?</span></u></b><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>  </span></b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Based on available evidence, children do not appear to be at higher risk for COVID-19 than adults. While some children and infants have been sick with COVID-19, adults make up most of the known cases to date. You can learn more about who is at higher risk for severe illness from COVID-19 at </span><span style="color:black;mso-color-alt:windowtext"><a target="_blank" href="https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/specific-groups/people-at-higher-risk.html"><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:#075290'>People who are at higher risk for severe illness</span></a></span><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>.<b></b></span></p>  <p style="background:white"><b><u><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:#007C91'>How can I protect my child from COVID-19 infection?</span></u></b><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:#007C91'>  </span></b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>You can encourage your child to help stop the spread of COVID-19 by teaching them to do the same things everyone should do to stay healthy.</span></p>  <ul type="disc">
<li style="background: white; color: black; font-family:; font-size: 12pt; font-style: normal; font-weight: 400;"><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:
     "Times New Roman"'>Avoid close contact with people who are sick.</span></li>  <li style="background: white; color: black; font-family:; font-size: 12pt; font-style: normal; font-weight: 400;"><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:
     "Times New Roman"'>Stay home when you are sick, except to get medical      care.</span></li>  <li style="background: white; color: black; font-family:; font-size: 12pt; font-style: normal; font-weight: 400;"><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:
     "Times New Roman"'>Cover your coughs and sneezes with a tissue and throw      the tissue in the trash.</span></li>  <li style="background: white; color: black; font-family:; font-size: 12pt; font-style: normal; font-weight: 400;"><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:
     "Times New Roman"'>Wash your hands often with soap and water for at least      20 seconds, especially after blowing your nose, coughing, or sneezing;      going to the bathroom; and before eating or preparing food.</span></li>  <li style="background: white; color: black; font-family:; font-size: 12pt; font-style: normal; font-weight: 400;"><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:
     "Times New Roman"'>If soap and water are not readily available, use an alcohol-based      hand sanitizer with at least 60% alcohol. Always wash hands with soap and      water if hands are visibly dirty.</span></li>  <li style="background: white; color: black; font-family:; font-size: 12pt; font-style: normal; font-weight: 400;"><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:
     "Times New Roman"'>Clean and disinfect frequently touched surfaces and      objects (e.g., tables, countertops, light switches, doorknobs, and cabinet      handles).</span></li>  <li style="background: white; color: black; font-family:; font-size: 12pt; font-style: normal; font-weight: 400;"><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:
     "Times New Roman"'>Launder items, including washable plush toys, as      appropriate and in accordance with the manufacturer’s instructions. If      possible, launder items using the warmest appropriate water setting for      the items and dry items completely. Dirty laundry from an ill person can      be washed with other people’s items.</span></li> </ul>
<p style="mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto;background:white"><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>You can find additional information on preventing COVID-19 at </span><span style="color:black;mso-color-alt:windowtext"><a target="_blank" href="https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/about/prevention.html"><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:#075290'>Prevention for 2019 Novel Coronavirus</span></a></span><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'> and at </span><span style="color:black;mso-color-alt:windowtext"><a target="_blank" href="https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/community/index.html"><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:#075290'>Preventing COVID-19 Spread in Communities</span></a></span><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>. Additional information on how COVID-19 is spread is available at </span><span style="color:black;
mso-color-alt:windowtext"><a target="_blank" href="https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/about/transmission.html"><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:#075290'>How COVID-19 Spreads</span></a></span><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:
"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>. More information on </span><span style="color:black;mso-color-alt:windowtext"><a target="_blank" href="https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/daily-life-coping/children.html"><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:#075290'>Children and Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19)</span></a></span><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'> is available online.</span></p>  <p style="background:white"><b><u><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:#007C91'>Are the symptoms of COVID-19 different in children than in adults?</span></u></b><b><span style='font-size:
12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:#007C91'>  </span></b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>No. The symptoms of COVID-19 are similar in children and adults. However, children with confirmed COVID-19 have generally presented with mild symptoms. Reported symptoms in children include cold-like symptoms, such as fever, runny nose, and cough. Vomiting and diarrhea have also been reported. It’s not known yet whether some children may be at higher risk for severe illness, for example, children with underlying medical conditions and special healthcare needs. There is much more to be learned about how the disease impacts children.</span><b><u><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:#007C91'></span></u></b></p>  <p style="background:white"><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:#007C91'> </span></p>  <p style="background:white"><b><u><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:#007C91'>Should children wear masks?</span></u></b><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:#007C91'>  </span></b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>CDC recommends that everyone 2 years and older wear a cloth face covering that covers their nose and mouth when they are out in the community. Cloth face coverings should NOT be put on babies or children younger than 2 because of the danger of suffocation. Children younger than 2 years of age are listed as an exception as well as anyone who has trouble breathing or is unconscious, incapacitated, or otherwise unable to remove the face covering without assistance.</span><b><u><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:#007C91'></span></u></b></p>  <p style="background:white"><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Wearing cloth face coverings is a public health measure people should take to reduce the spread of COVID-19 in addition to (not instead of) social distancing, frequent hand cleaning ,and other everyday preventive actions. A cloth face covering is not intended to protect the wearer but may prevent the spread of virus from the wearer to others. This would be especially important if someone is infected but does not have symptoms. </span></p>  <p style="background:white"><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:#007C91'> </span></p>  <p style="background:white"><b><u><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:#007C91'>How do I prepare my children in case of COVID-19 outbreak in our community?</span></u></b><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:#007C91'>  </span></b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Outbreaks can be stressful for adults and children. Talk with your children about the outbreak, try to stay calm, and reassure them that they are safe. If appropriate, explain to them that most illness from COVID-19 seems to be mild. </span><span style="color:black;mso-color-alt:windowtext"><a target="_blank" href="https://www.cdc.gov/childrenindisasters/helping-children-cope.html"><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:#075290'>Children respond differently to stressful situations than adults</span></a></span><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>. CDC offers </span><span style="color:black;mso-color-alt:windowtext"><a target="_blank" href="https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/community/schools-childcare/talking-with-children.html"><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:#075290'>resources</span></a></span><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'> to help talk with children about COVID-19.</span><b><u><span style='font-size:
12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:#007C91'></span></u></b></p>  <p style="background:white"><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:#007C91'> </span></p>  <p style="background:white"><b><u><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:#007C91'>What steps should parents take to protect children during a community outbreak?</span></u></b></p>  <p style="mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto;background:white"><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>This is a new virus and we are still learning about it, but so far, there does not seem to be a lot of illness in children. Most illness, including serious illness, is happening in adults of working age and older adults. However, children do get the virus and become ill. Discourage children and teens from gathering in other public places while school is dismissed to help slow the spread of COVID-19 in the community.</span></p>  <br></span><br><div align="right">
		<br clear="both"><br>
</div>
		
		
		
	
		
		
		
		
		
